biography:
Emerging from the Scottish Highlands, KAVARI is an electronic music artist and DJ based in Glasgow, known for her transgressive art and distinct, high-intensity style that blends industrial, ambient, club, and noise music.

A leading figure in the UK underground electronic music scene, KAVARI draws from the legacy of British experimental sound while pushing it into new territory. Her work focuses on distortion, contrast, and structural disruption—challenging conventions in both underground and commercial music spaces. Bringing the fringe to the mainstream, and the mainstream to the fringe. Her innovative productions and live performances have earned international recognition, including praise from IDM pioneer Aphex Twin, who called her music “some of the most brilliant, most interesting kicking electronic music” in recent years.

Recognised globally and central to the evolution of the UK and Scottish underground scenes, KAVARI continues to redefine the boundaries of club culture, electronic music, and DJ performance.

biography: The challenging, visceral music produced by Houston's Rabit (Eric C. Burton) incorporates influences such as grime, post-industrial sound design, and the chopped-and-screwed rap of his hometown. Initially receiving attention for his take on the angular U.K. grime sound with a series of EPs during the early 2010s, Rabit's intense, violent full-length Communion (2015) crystallized his influences. From there, he ventured further into the unknown, releasing more abstract full-lengths such as Life After Death (2018), in addition to several screw mixtapes. Rabit has collaborated with Björk, Dedekind Cut, Chino Amobi, and others, and he runs the well-regarded experimental label Halcyon Veil. Rabit debuted in 2012 with Terminator, an EP fusing juke and grime. Released on Austin, Texas' #FEELINGS label, it featured a Traxman remix of the title track. Rabit's reach extended as he made overseas connections. The follow-up EP Sun Showers, released in 2013, came out through Japan's Diskotopia, while a handful of 2013-2014 singles, including a release split with Logos, surfaced on Dublin, Ireland's Glacial Sound. In 2015, the producer joined up with the Tri Angle label for another EP, Baptizm. Later that year, he founded the Halcyon Veil label and released the full-length Communion, which made the gender and political issues in his previous work more explicit. Two limited, self-released albums (Supreme and Excommunicate) appeared in 2016, in addition to collaborations with Dedekind Cut and Chino Amobi. Second proper full-length Les Fleurs du Mal, a departure from his more rhythmic earlier style, followed in 2017. During the year, Rabit co-produced "Losss," a track on Björk's Grammy-nominated full-length Utopia. In 2018, Rabit released the full-length Life After Death and the EP Toe in the Bardo Pond. He also released Cry Alone Die Alone and Bricks in a Drought, two mixtapes which faithfully paid tribute to DJ Screw's pioneering chopped-and-screwed sound. A third screw tape, The Dope Show, followed in 2019. ~ Andy Kellman & Paul Simpson, Rovi

biography:
Ahmed El Ghazoly, aka ZULI (stylized in all caps), is a musician, producer, and sound artist from Cairo, Egypt.

Internationally, ZULI is best known for his boundary-pushing releases on Lee Gamble’s UIQ, including a string of EPs and his debut LP Terminal — a record that fuses experimental hip-hop, club music, and deep listening. His Trigger Finger EP, released via Italy’s Haunter Records, gained wide acclaim and was later remixed by artists like TSVI, AYA, and Acre.

In 2019, ZULI co-founded irsh with fellow Cairene DJ Rama — a project that began as a video series and evolved into a label and club night.

In Cairo, ZULI is recognized for his work in the hip-hop scene with rapper Abyusif, as well as his role in shaping the city’s electronic underground as part of the collective Kairo Is Koming (KIK). He co-founded the alternative music venue and club VENT (2013–2015), later transforming it into a namesake festival and club night.

ZULI’s diverse sound has earned support from a wide spectrum of artists including Aphex Twin, Autechre, Ben UFO, Bradley Zero, and Richie Hawtin. Recent releases include the album Lambda and the EP Care on Subtext Recordings.

He has hosted a monthly show on NTS Radio since 2016, regularly featuring guest mixes by emerging DJs and close collaborators.

biography:
Ziúr is an experimental producer/musician and a fixture in Berlin’s rich musical topography.

It seems as though she produces her releases in the way someone scoring a television series does, gathering and arranging their selections for each episode … isolating and apprehending definitive scenes and memorializing their ethos in song. Soundtracks, much like her release “Antifate”, guide the listener through radically different emotional states, yet somehow still offer an idea of what underpins a show’s (or in this case an album’s) particular hues.

Ziúr produces music within such a scope, expansive, rich and diverse in texture. The sounds are simultaneously machinistic and deeply anthropomorphic, toying with mechanical isolation and the chaotic spectrum of human emotion. Unlike a soundtrack or score, there is no film to which one can turn to narrativize the music … there is only evocative sounds reaching from each song towards the cybernetic sublime.

biography: Shanghai-based Tess Sun, better known as Hyph11E, produces and DJs an intense, post-industrial hybrid of bass-heavy club styles and advanced sound design. Releases such as 2020's Aperture fuse footwork, gqom, noise, and breakcore while exploring themes related to biology and geology. Originally from Hebei, China, Sun grew up practicing piano for several hours a day. She eventually worked at a recording studio in Beijing, and after a friend took her to see Japanese dubstep producer Goth-Trad at Shanghai club Dada in 2014, she quit her job and moved to the city. Recording and performing as Hyph11E, her music was first heard on a 2016 compilation that launched the Shanghai-based Genome6.66Mbp label. Quickly attracting the attention of experimental club DJs and producers worldwide, Hyph11E signed to SVBKVLT, another Shanghai collective, and released her debut EP, Vanishing Cinema, in 2017, including remixes by M.E.S.H. and Tzusing. Performing frequently throughout Asia, she began making European performances in 2018, and an appearance at Uganda's Nyege Nyege Festival in 2019 coincided with the release of the EP Slip B, her collaboration with Kenyan producer Slikback. Hyph11E's debut album, Aperture, themed around the parasitic nature of holes, arrived in 2020. Its lead single, "Barnacles," featured a remix by Hyperdub founder Kode9. ~ Paul Simpson, Rovi

biography:
Puce Mary is the solo moniker of experimental musician and sound artist, Frederikke Hoffmeier.
Oft-identified with the now-generation of industrial noise  - Puce Mary has a reputation for intense live performances that span from gripping renditions of cinematic compositions to the full-on fury of off-the-cuff harsh noise. 
With countless releases, performances and collaborations with artists such as Kali Malone, Drew McDowall and Loke Rahbek, Puce Mary has reached wide acclaim for her powerful and unique blend of modern industrial/noise music.  
Born in 1989 in Denmark, Hoffmeier started her career in Copenhagen’s underground music scene, closely affiliated with Posh Isolation and the venue/music collective Mayhem KBH. 

With her most recent and critically acclaimed album “The Drought” released on PAN, Hoffmeier expands the field of sound more broadly than before, unfurling a complex sonic and literary narrative of tension and release. Amidst disquieting dynamics and surreal cinematics, she voices existential soliloquies, while swarms of sound lurk and blasts interrupt. The Drought is for the ages to be sure  – “I find myself feeling like decades have passed” she intones on Red Desert – but it is also unmistakably contemporary, giving new urgency to the fabrics she digs – be it the dense textures of Bianchi or litterature of Baudelaire.

biography: Sote is the primary moniker of Ata Ebtekar, one of Iran's most prominent electronic and experimental musicians. Initially starting out as a techno artist during the '90s, his work gradually became more distorted and abstract, earning the attention of labels like Warp. Later on, he received acclaim for fusing Persian classical traditions with electro-acoustic music. Ebtekar was born in Hamburg, Germany and spent his youth in both Iran and Germany. He grew up listening to new wave and industrial music, and after his family moved to San Francisco when he was 16, he was introduced to techno music. He began studying sound design, and he released a few techno and trance tracks as Atax during the late '90s. His first single as Sote was Electric Deaf, an intense drum'n'bass/breakcore epic issued by none other than Warp in 2002. The more abstract XOXO EP followed on Dielectric Records in 2003, and the haunting electro-acoustic full-length Dastgaah, which largely abandoned the rhythmic elements of his prior work, appeared in 2006. The 2007 EP Wake Up (on Record Label Records) was a return to techno and drum'n'bass, but some of his most accomplished experimental work to date was released as the second disc of Sub Rosa's double CD Persian Electronic Music: Yesterday and Today 1966-2006, which also featured the music of Iranian composer Alireza Mashayekhi. Ebtekar, who had moved back to Tehran by this point, also performed Mashayekhi's works, along with the Iranian Orchestra for New Music, on a 2009 release titled Ornamental. Ebtekar collaborated with composer/pianist Mazdak Khamda on an album titled Sonic Within, initially released as a cassette by Digitalis in 2010 and later issued on vinyl by 333 Recordings/2 Hed. The solo album Dear Iran, Miniature Engines Throb in Time for Your Beating Heart appeared on Merzbild in 2013. Ebtekar returned to his Sote moniker, as well as more rhythmic, techno/industrial-influenced material, with the 2014 LP Architectonic, which was released by Morphine Records. Arrhythmia, created on modular synthesizers, was released digitally by Record Label Records in 2015. Hardcore Sounds from Tehran, a cassette containing edits of live performances, was released by Opal Tapes in 2016. Additionally, Repitch released 10inch04, a single containing previously unreleased tracks recorded during the 1990s, and the EP Hyper-urban 20 30 appeared on Ge-Stell. In 2017, Opal Tapes released Sote's Sacred Horror in Design, an album of electro-acoustic music created as part of a commission from Berlin's CTM Festival. ~ Paul Simpson, Rovi

biography:
Sightless Pit is the project of duo Lee Buford (The Body) and Dylan Walker (Full of Hell). Buford and Walker are born collaborators, known for their ability to subvert musical expectations, transcend genre and plunge headlong into the unknown. Their work with the likes of Thou, Uniform, Merzbow, and Nothing, taken together with their The Body & Full of Hell albums, have established each as singular voices and masterful alchemists of heavy music. The duo shares an affection for rhythm-based beat music, disparate electronic genres, dub, as well as darkly-hued atmospheric ambience. 

The duo's 2023 new album Lockstep Bloodwar exceeds expectations by stunningly combining the noise and confrontational posturing they are both well known for with pulsing and kaleidoscopic electronic samples, drum machines, and grizzled synths. Across the album, the two highly inventive musical omnivores are buoyed by an astounding menagerie of eclectic and celebrated collaborators.

Daniel Ochieng Odhis Copsey, known artistically as Kop-Z, is a Kenyan-British audio-visual artist whose creative journey is profoundly shaped by his upbringing on the industrial outskirts of Salford. His artistic expression represents a vibrant fusion of diverse musical genres, drawing influences from rave, post-punk, reggae, jungle, and the rich sounds embedded in his East African heritage.

From a young age, Kop-Z developed a deep interest in the history and geography of his environment, coupled with a fascination for the digital realm. His passion for video games, science fiction, and computer technology has significantly informed his artistic vision, allowing him to seamlessly merge both physical and digital worlds.

biography: ELIZAVETA DE ELFIS - is a composer, sound designer who focuses on conveying history, meaning, and emotion through her music. Her works blend elements of academic and electronic music, and she does not limit herself to specific genres or instrument kits. In August 2023, she released her first official track, "end of artificial bloom" in collaboration with YouTuber LuzLunar. This soulful piano composition allows listeners to interpret its meaning for themselves. ELIZAVETA says: "i'm glad that this music can mean different things to everyone. Due to the vague title and the lack of text in the music, everyone can decide for themselves what this music is about. And i'm sure there's no wrong answer here!" In December of the same year, she delighted fans with the electronic track "Best Friend". ELIZAVETA created her own electronic instruments very similar to those used on old game consoles. But due to the fact that these were not sampled instruments, ELIZAVETA could edit the sound in any way to make it perfectly match the composition. This charming song was released on the birthday of her close friend, Rom1o, whose covers of various music are gaining tens of thousands of views on YouTube, and was warmly received by listeners.

biography: Mike Hollis, also known as x.nte, is a music producer who creates a unique blend of breakcore, noise music, jungle, and DnB. Their music style is characterized by high energy, intense soundscapes, and fast-paced rhythms, which are complimented by the addition of piano melodies and ambient sound tones.  In addition to these genres, they incorporate elements from 90s nu metal, such as guitar riffs and hard-hitting gabber kickdrums, which add a distinct edge to their sound. What makes x.nte's music truly stand out, however, is the incorporation of vocal samples with anti-capitalist sentiments, quips on mental health, and themes of existential dread. These themes are personal to x.nte and represent a deeper, more meaningful message behind their music. The use of vocal samples in their tracks add an extra layer of texture and meaning, allowing listeners to connect with their music on a deeper level. Interestingly, the name x.nte is an abbreviation for "anxious, nervous, & tired endlessly," which speaks to the mental health themes that are present in their music. The combination of these disparate elements creates a unique sound that is both familiar and new. The addition of piano melodies and ambient sound tones provides a softer contrast to the harsher electronic sounds, creating an interesting mix of textures. x.nte's music has a clear message and purpose that speaks to listeners who are looking for something beyond the typical club music experience.
